  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_884266736" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/884266736" />
    <a title="Crystal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/182835-crystal"><img alt="Crystal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608764683p2/182835.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/884266736?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Crystal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Crystal" href="/user/show/182835-crystal">Crystal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/182835-crystal?shelf=chick-lit">chick-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer884266736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10326356951247598131">I&apos;m not sure what I was expecting when I picked this book up. I&apos;m trying to read writing with more diverse experiences and points of view, and I have a vague memory of seeing the movie and enjoying it--mostly Angela Bassett&apos;s fiercess and that crazy scene where she destroys her husband&apos;s car. <br/>So either my memory is faulty or the book is a lot different than the movie. Honestly, I didn&apos;t like this very much. And even though I didn&apos;t really like this book, I don&apos;t know if it&apos;s because the characte</span>
  <span id="freeText10326356951247598131" style="display:none">I'm not sure what I was expecting when I picked this book up. I'm trying to read writing with more diverse experiences and points of view, and I have a vague memory of seeing the movie and enjoying it--mostly Angela Bassett's fiercess and that crazy scene where she destroys her husband's car. <br />So either my memory is faulty or the book is a lot different than the movie. Honestly, I didn't like this very much. And even though I didn't really like this book, I don't know if it's because the character are as awful as I think they are, or at least partly because of cultural differences. There was honestly only one person I liked consistently in this story--Gloria. Gloria worked hard, was a responsible parent, and cared for everyone else in her life. She was irresponsible in her eating habits, and paid the health prices for it, but she was a good person, a good mom, a good boss, and a good friend. Also, she didn't bang any married men, which puts her leagues above her other friends. <br />I was honestly horrified how much infidelity went on in this book, involving characters that were meant to be sympathetic. Bernadine's husband is supposed to be so horrible partly because he cheated on her for a long time and then left her for someone else. So why is it OK for Bernadine and her friends to turn around and do the same thing, often multiple times/ on an extended basis? I've escaped from a controlling, mentally abusive relationship too, and I know there's a certain feeling of wildness at first--just because you can. But just because you suddenly COULD do something doesn't mean you should or make it remotely OK. Bernadine needed to take some lessons on being there for her kids from Gloria, because frankly, through much of the book, I thought someone should call child services on her. Plus, her sexual/ romantic choices were just ick. A revolving door of lovers, some of them married, just seems nasty to me. <br />I actually had a difficult time getting invested in any of the relationships, because there was such a revolving door leading up to them. Multiple sex scenes with multiple lovers for each of the non-Gloria women, most of them more gross than sexy--after awhile I knew not to get my hopes up when a character was introduces. maybe it's realistic...but no thanks. Just no. <br />Savannah was probably the other most sympathetic character for me. (I'm not even going to talk about the selfish, immature, crazy hot mess that was Robin. Her ending? *shakes head*) But Savannah was a responsible, hardworking person and a good friend (no matter how the women all talked to each other--I assume that's just a cultural difference?). I appreciated her strength and I wanted a good ending for her. But her sexual choices weren't much better than the other three.<br />oh, and don't even get me started on the ridiculously dated writing. Everything had to be a current name brand--food, cigarettes, TV shows, clothing and shoe brands, cars, etc. I find that kind of writing tacky anyway, but reading it so many years after it was written, it felt even more distracting and unnecessary than usual. <br />By the end, due to my frustrations with most of the women's choices and my lack of investment in the male characters and their relationships, I couldn't buy into their (happy-ish) endings. The endings felt forced or cliche, somehow, and in some cases, very not deserved. Overall, a very unsatisfying read, and not an author I'd seek out again. <br /><br />PS....aware that I'm speaking of a sub-culture about which I'm unfortunately not as knowledgeable as I would like to be, I'm totally willing and open to any information or explanations that could change my understanding of the book and its characters. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10326356951247598131" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

