    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1095632087" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1095632087" />
    <a title="Beverlee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19383221-beverlee"><img alt="Beverlee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609106848p2/19383221.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1095632087?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beverlee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beverlee" href="/user/show/19383221-beverlee">Beverlee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671537456" href="/book/show/1603515.Waiting_to_Exhale">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19383221-beverlee?shelf=rerun-rereads">rerun-rereads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19383221-beverlee?shelf=quarantine-catch-me-up">quarantine-catch-me-up</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19383221-beverlee?shelf=owned-books">owned-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1095632087" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14962637207601217831">I think it’s a sign of growth when you can revisit a book nearly 25 years later and it’s like reading a new book. Admission #1-pretty certain I saw the movie before I read the book. Then again I was 15. This is a book that I took at face value without really thinking about the message. Savannah, Bernadine, Gloria, and Robin are friends living in Phoenix. They are in the 35-38 age range, all are relatively successful in their chosen professions. The drama is centered around the men in their lives</span>
  <span id="freeText14962637207601217831" style="display:none">I think it’s a sign of growth when you can revisit a book nearly 25 years later and it’s like reading a new book. Admission #1-pretty certain I saw the movie before I read the book. Then again I was 15. This is a book that I took at face value without really thinking about the message. Savannah, Bernadine, Gloria, and Robin are friends living in Phoenix. They are in the 35-38 age range, all are relatively successful in their chosen professions. The drama is centered around the men in their lives. Bernadine is going through a divorce after eleven years of being a devoted wife. Savannah is newly moved to Phoenix and is chasing a career goal of becoming a television producer and finding Mr. Right. Gloria is the owner of a popular salon but somewhere along the way she buried her dream of happily ever after and her focus is primarily on her teenage son. Robin is the youngest of the quartet and is described as “dizzy”. She’s in an on/off relationship with Russell, a man not married to her. The other men in her life, Michael &amp; Troy are not astrological matches, therefore they’re unsuitable. <br />Admission #2-the references to material things and popular culture are dated but that doesn’t change the emotions felt when reading. I so wanted everyone to find what brings them peace and fulfillment. What I don’t like or understand is the idea that life has to contain a partner to be seen as complete. It’s not real life, but these women possess so much more patience with the men in their lives than I would if I was in their shoes. Admission #3-so what’s the point of it all? Waiting to Exhale means what to who? Is it when you finally reach a desired moment in life when everything is established and moving in the direction you want and it’s time to relax and enjoy? Or does it mean taking a moment to examine what’s wrong and what’s right in one’s life and hitting a “reset” button if needed? Another way to put it, what’s more important the journey or the destination? <br />Other 💭 <br />What kind of commentary is shared about relationships between Black women and men, particularly the author’s intent? My opinion is that McMillan is aiming to show that happiness will come, maybe not the way we picture it. <br />What about gender roles? McMillan seemingly writes Robin as having little common sense and sexually liberated. Yet Savannah &amp; Bernadine are presented as intelligent yet they are sexually active and not necessarily in committed relationships. Gloria is the only character presented as celibate and she is the one who ends up in a lasting relationship (so close to revealing a spoiler from the sequel). Gloria is also described as being overweight and that’s supposedly a hinderance in her finding Mr. Right. Is this a back-handed way to compliment Gloria in the end or am I being too sensitive? Is this a different way of projecting patriarchal beliefs by clothing it as feminist text? Or is it feminist in presenting the many ways African American exercise agency over their sexuality? <br />4 stars for being honest. Honesty is not always pretty and cloaked in respectability. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14962637207601217831" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


